x4freetext: 140 g of cyanoguanidine (NCNC(NH2)2) powder containing
93 g of natural nitrogen in which the abundance of
N-14 is 99.6%. This sample was contained in a hollow
disk (diameter = 152 mm, thickness = 12 mm) of 0.13
mm thick plastic film. The sample was oriented at 15
degrees to the direction of the photon beam.
flight path = 10 m.
Each of eight neutron detectors consisted of a
25 mm thick NE104 plastic scintillator of diameter
125 mm viewed by two Phillips xp1040 photomultiplier
tubes.
Statistical errors are presented.
Data were compiled at SCJAD of Saratov
State University.
Corrected by V.Varlamov, V.Mclane.
Corrected by V.Varlamov: REACTION,
STATUS, HISTORY, dates, lowercase.
Corrected by SD and VV: AUTHOR, PART-DET,
EN-SEC, small corrections in several SUBENTs.
Relative number of neutrons
The energy spectra were corrected for
a) the dead time of detectors,
b) the cosmic background,
c) the background sample data,
d) the neutron detection efficiency.
Each obtained laboratory-frame neutron energy
spectrum was divided at each energy by the measured
neutron detection efficiency and then converted to
the c.m. frame.
Photoneutron energy spectra for end-point energies of
20.5, 22.5, 24.5, 26.5 MeV were measured using
time-of-flight techniques at eight angles from 48 to
139 degrees in 13 degrees step. Ground-state angular
distributions and (g,n0) cross sections were obtained
from measured spectra. Coefficients of a Legendre
polynomial fitted to the data were interpreted in
terms of a simple single particle nuclear model.
Data from Fig. 4 of Nucl.Phys.,A337(1980)503.

corrections in SUBENTs 010 and 011.

x4freetext: The ground-state data were corrected for the
bremsstrahlung spectra.
Only neutrons of the highest 3.5 MeV wide region near
the tip of each spectrum represent purely
ground-state transition because the transitions to
the first excited state of N-13 at 2.36 MeV are
negligible.
The ground-state data have been obtained by
fitting of a series of Legendre polynomials to the
eight highest 3.5 MeV regions of neutron spectra for
each end-point measurement. The zero order
coefficient of  this series has been corrected by
division by the photon distribution shape and has
been represented as the total ground-state cross
section.
The ground-state data were compared with the results
of measurement of cross-sections for N-14(g,p0) and
C-13(g,p0) reaction.

x4freetext: The total
photon absorption strengths calculation.
For reactions to the ground state in N-13, it appears
that most of the photon absorption in the giant
resonance region studied forms 2- states in N-14,
which are decayed by d-wave neutron emission. Some
evidence was found for the existence of 0- strength
at about 22.5 MeV (the peak of the cross section).
The results are in general consistent with an
identification of the (g,n0) process with the
promotion of a p1/2 neutron to the s-d shell. Little
or no E2 or M1 absorption was observed. Comparison
with photoproton measurement shows some evidence for
a small amount of isospin t = 0 mixing also near
22.5 MeV. The results of the experiment have yielded a
cross section which represents only a small fraction
(17%) of the possible neutron-producing decays from
the giant resonance of N-14. Comparison with
calculations of the ground-state cross section shows
reasonable agreement if the theoretical results are
displaced upwards in energy of about 1 MeV.
Data from Fig. 5 of Nucl.Phys.,A337(1980)503.
